{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487056"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:55:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:55:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"241"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/241"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.03,0.24,0.19,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90581"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/241"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74792"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1317"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"3856"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5788"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41925"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90581"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department by ambulance following an intentional drug overdose as a suicide attempt. Two hours ago, she swallowed forty 10mg tablets of oxycodone with a bottle of wine. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears drowsy with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 9. Her pulse rate is 60/min, blood pressure 110/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 8/min, oxygen saturation 90% on room air, and temperature 35.9\u00b0C. Her pupils are pinpoint bilaterally and she snores unless her head is supported by jaw thrust.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to continuing jaw thrust and oxygen, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous flumazenil","Activated charcoal via nasogastric tube","Commence naloxone infusion","Intubation and mechanical ventilation","Bolus intravenous or intramuscular naloxone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic signs of opioid overdose: respiratory depression (respiratory rate 8/min), decreased level of consciousness (GCS 9), pinpoint pupils, and hypoxia. The history of oxycodone ingestion confirms the diagnosis. The immediate priority is to reverse the opioid effect on the respiratory centre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBolus intravenous or intramuscular naloxone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. Naloxone is a competitive opioid receptor antagonist that rapidly reverses opioid effects. Initial bolus doses (typically 0.4-2 mg IV/IM) should be titrated to restore adequate respiratory function without precipitating complete withdrawal. The goal is to improve respiratory rate and oxygen saturation while maintaining airway reflexes, not necessarily to fully reverse sedation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence naloxone infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate after initial bolus doses have demonstrated effectiveness, particularly because oxycodone has a longer duration of action than naloxone. However, titrated bolus doses are needed first to establish the effective dose before starting an infusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubation and mechanical ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E may eventually be necessary if the patient fails to respond to naloxone or if there are other complications. However, it is not the most appropriate next step when a potentially reversible cause of respiratory depression is present and a specific antidote is available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E via nasogastric tube is not indicated in this scenario. The ingestion occurred two hours ago, making gastrointestinal decontamination less effective. Additionally, administering charcoal to a patient with a depressed level of consciousness carries significant aspiration risk unless the airway is protected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous flumazenil\u003C/strong\u003E is a benzodiazepine antagonist and would not reverse opioid-induced respiratory depression. It would be inappropriate in this case where the clinical picture and history clearly indicate opioid toxicity rather than benzodiazepine overdose.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Naloxone should be administered promptly in cases of suspected opioid overdose with respiratory depression.","Titrated bolus doses of naloxone are preferred initially over continuous infusion in acute opioid overdose.","Airway management with jaw thrust and oxygen supplementation are critical first steps in managing opioid overdose."],"references":["Boyer EW. Management of Opioid Analgesic Overdose N Engl J Med 2012; 367:146-55. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3739053/","Opioid poisoning: general management. In:\u00a0eTG complete\u00a0[online]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2020. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74792"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"241"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74792"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T12:29:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T12:29:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"241"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90581"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":